substantiated by the evidence. In accessible prose, Wolf argues that a public obsession with health and what she calls “total motherhood” has made breastfeeding a cause célèbre, and that public discussions of breastfeeding say more about infatuation with personal responsibility and perfect mothering in America than they do about the concrete benefits of the breast.Why has breastfeeding re-asserted itself over the last twenty years, and why are the government, the scientific and medical communities, and so many mothers so invested in the idea? Parsing the rhetoric of expert advice, including the recent National Breastfeeding Awareness Campaign, and rigorously questioning the scientific evidence, Wolf uncovers a path by which a mother can feel informed and confident about how best to feed her thriving infant-whether flourishing by breast or by bottle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBreastfeedingxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aBreastfeedingxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aBreastfeedingxSocial aspects. 0aBreastfeeding. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAmericas.  aBest.  aBreast.  aJoan.  aWolf.  aassertion.  ablame.  acultivating.  afeet.  ahyperbolically.  alays.  amythic.  aobsession.  aparanoid.  aprevention.  arisk.  athis.  awith.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479481440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814794814.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814795255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814795255/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  a